    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 18th with a clear focal point in **Yordan Alvarez**, who anchors the lineup with an elite 81.48 score. Facing Pallante, **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a strong platoon advantage and a favorable pitcher profile, making him our primary offensive engine. **Colt Keith** also presents a high-upside play at 69.64; his promotion to the three-hole against Bello, combined with a significant park factor boost, positions him to capitalize on early RBI opportunities. Meanwhile, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** earns a start at 65.42 largely due to his elite stolen base potential; even from the eight-hole, his dynamic platoon edge and the specific timing of the opposing pitcher\u2019s delivery against the run make him a vital asset in our pursuit of the scarcest category.\n\nNavigating the rotation against top-tier arms requires tactical discipline. While **Trea Turner** and **Kyle Schwarber** face a formidable challenge in Sale, their scores remain resilient at 55.23 and 53.83, respectively, bolstered by their high spots in the order and inherent ability to impact the scoreboard regardless of pitcher dominance. The most difficult personnel decision involved **Junior Caminero**, whose 55.03 score was essentially neck-and-neck with the remainder of our utility group. Ultimately, the optimizer favored keeping him in the lineup despite the tough matchup against Skenes to maintain our aggressive ceiling. We continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, **Hyeseong Kim**, **Zac Veen**, and **Victor Scott II**, all of whom remain sidelined, while keeping secondary options like **Lars Nootbaar**, **Josh Smith**, **Dillon Dingler**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, and **Luis Pena** ready should roster flexibility dictate a pivot. \n\nBe advised that today\u2019s lineup rests on the assumption of **Kazuma Okamoto** batting seventh; should the official card shift him lower, his 53.49 score may contract further. We are also treading carefully with *